Since then, more new species have been reported from both marine and fresh waters (
Gagarin & Nguyen 2006
;
Gagarin & Thanh 2008
;
Hourston & Warwick 2010
;
Wu et al. 2000
;
Zhang 2005
;
Zou 2000
). Currently, 26 species are recognised for the genus
Parodontophora
Timm, 1963
(http://www.marinespecies.org/index.php and http:// nemys.ugent.be).

Undisturbed sediment samples were collected from coastal areas of Fujian Province, East China Sea, i.e., intertidal sandy beaches of Huoshan Island in Zhangzhou City; intertidal mudflat of Baihajiao Island and Fenglin mangrove mudflats in Xiamen City; mangrove mudflats in the estuary of Zhang River and Jiulong River in Zhangzhou City; mangrove mudflats in the estuary of Luoyang River in Quanzhou City; Wanwu mangrove mudflats in Ningde City (showed in
Figure 1
). Collected samples were fixed with 5 % formalin in filtered seawater. In laboratory, samples were stained with 0.1 % of rose Bengal for more than 24 hours. All meiofauna were extracted from the sediment through decantation and/or Ludox centrifugation (
Jonge & Bouwman 1977
). Each sample was washed into a lined Petri dish and the meiofauna were sorted under a stereoscopic microscope (Nikon smz 800 ). Nematodes were transferred into a solution containing, by volume, 90 % freshwater, 5 % of the 95 % ethanol and 5 % of glycerol in a cavity block to let ethanol slowly evaporate and then mounted in glycerol on permanent slides (
Seinhorst 1959
). The description was obtained under a differential interference contrast microscopy (Nikon
80 i
), and the morphology was draw via a camera lucida. All holotypes and paratypes were deposited in the Third Institute of Oceanography, State Oceanic Administration, Xiamen, China .

